        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1873-06-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1873-06-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="191"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d191">
                <head>No. 189.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SET1" type="from">Sir Edward Thornton</persName> to
                        Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HF1" type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1873-06-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 19, 1873</date>. (Received June
                        19.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer you to a note addressed
                    to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_JBD1">Bancroft Davis</persName> by Mr. Pakenham on
                    the 10th of September, 1871, asking the consideration by the Government of the
                    United States of a proposal made by the government of Newfoundland that American
                    fishermen should be admitted to the right of taking seals within the territorial
                    jurisdiction of Newfoundland on the condition of the admission of the produce of
                    the Newfoundland seal-fishery into the United States free of duty.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_JBD1">Bancroft Davis</persName> replied, on the 23d of
                    the same month, that the subject would receive consideration, but that the
                    proposal was one which needed congressional approval before it could be
                    definitively accepted by the Department of State.</p>
                <p>In compliance with an instruction which I have received this morning from Earl
                    Granville, I have the honor to inquire whether any steps have been taken by your
                    Department with a view to carry out the proposal made by the government of
                    Newfoundland, with regard to which Mr. <persName corresp="#p_JBD1">Bancroft
                        Davis</persName> was at the time informed that Her Majesty’s government
                    would be glad if it could be acceded to.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SET1">EDW’D THORNTON</persName>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
